      "content_html": "<img src=\"https://assets.newatlas.com/dims4/default/a4ae2a3/2147483647/strip/true/crop/2199x1154+0+156/resize/1200x630!/quality/85/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fnewatlas-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F34%2F1e%2F98c4ab094d98b45ebf1dc2e8c0a4%2F1-20260408-115512.jpg&amp;na.image_optimisation=0\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\n<p><img alt=\"For scale, the Eyeris Zen isn't as tall as a baby bottle, but definitely bigger than a lemon\" src=\"https://assets.newatlas.com/dims4/default/7dc15b5/2147483647/strip/true/crop/2199x1466+0+0/resize/1440x960!/format/webp/quality/85/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fnewatlas-brightspot.s3.amazonaws.com%2F34%2F1e%2F98c4ab094d98b45ebf1dc2e8c0a4%2F1-20260408-115512.jpg\" /><p>I've purchased a couple of massaging dodads in my day – the ubiquitous early-2000s \"shiatsu back massager with heat\" kind of thing you'd see on TV and whatnot – but those roller balls always end up just jabbing my sacrum or spine, making me more irritated than relaxed. So I gave up on gizmos of questionable quality and decided I'd continue my usual once a decade or so visit to an actual pro.</p><p><a href=\"https://newatlas.com/wearables/review-renpho-headspace-eyeris-zen-massager/\">Continue Reading</a></p><p><b>Category:</b> <a href=\"https://newatlas.com/wearables/\">Wearables</a>, <a href=\"https://newatlas.com/consumer-tech/\">Consumer Tech</a>, <a href=\"https://newatlas.com/technology/\">Technology</a></p><p><b>Tags:</b> <a href=\"https://newatlas.com/tag/massager/\" rel=\"tag\">Massager</a>, <a href=\"https://newatlas.com/tag/headset/\" rel=\"tag\">Headset</a>, <a href=\"https://newatlas.com/tag/eye/\" rel=\"tag\">Eye</a>, <a href=\"https://newatlas.com/reviews/\" rel=\"tag\">Reviews</a></p>",
